1
00:00:00,875 --> 00:00:07,581
Does Buddhism stifle creativity in the birth of ideas?

2
00:00:16,451 --> 00:00:18,713
The mind creates.

3
00:00:18,753 --> 00:00:19,634
It's always creating, isn't it?

4
00:00:19,754 --> 00:00:21,635
You can't stop it from creating.

5
00:00:21,696 --> 00:00:22,836
It's the purpose of the mind.

6
00:00:23,057 --> 00:00:25,739
I mean, that's what you might call, define the mind.

7
00:00:25,760 --> 00:00:28,283
The mind is intention, isn't it?

8
00:00:29,478 --> 00:00:31,719
I think it's something to do with time as well.

9
00:00:35,344 --> 00:00:42,652
And something to do with karma in the widest sense of that word.

10
00:00:44,293 --> 00:00:54,665
Meaning that at any point in time there's a junction of what is coming out of one's own mind and what is coming into it from the outside.

11
00:00:55,906 --> 00:00:59,451
And so there's always, there's got to be always some sort of creativity

12
00:00:59,869 --> 00:01:05,415
as we move from moment to moment.

13
00:01:05,436 --> 00:01:14,885
So even just in this walk this afternoon we got to the top and the wind was so great and that we had to be creative and come back down.

14
00:01:17,728 --> 00:01:22,513
The idea was to continue walking but the conditions were contrary to our expectations.

15
00:01:24,756 --> 00:01:27,379
But just in the wider sense of creativity

16
00:01:27,697 --> 00:01:57,382
in the sense of creating art after the Buddha's enlightenment after the Buddha's awakening it's not as though his mind stopped in fact the first thought that came into his mind was who can I teach this to there's already a movement outward from that initial insight

17
00:01:57,936 --> 00:01:59,179
and the great insights he had.

18
00:02:00,421 --> 00:02:04,768
And of course he spent the rest of his life, 40 years, being creative.

19
00:02:06,710 --> 00:02:12,881
If you read the discourses, they're very much personal conversations with different people.

20
00:02:14,883 --> 00:02:21,835
The later discourses, the ones right at the end of the book, in the long discourses, become much more set pieces.

21
00:02:22,725 --> 00:02:29,013
But if you read a lot of them, they're just somebody asking a question and him responding.

22
00:02:29,032 --> 00:02:31,455
And he responds normally in two ways.

23
00:02:31,635 --> 00:02:35,939
First of all, in a rational way, a logical rational way.

24
00:02:36,580 --> 00:02:42,266
And then he always likes to give an example, a metaphor, for those who think better that way.

25
00:02:42,526 --> 00:02:43,147
That's how it's put.

26
00:02:43,527 --> 00:02:49,694
For those who think more energetically, he expresses it that way.

27
00:02:49,895 --> 00:02:53,399
I wouldn't go as far as to say that he was a poet or anything of that nature.

28
00:02:55,159 --> 00:03:03,308
But then all religion finds expression for these truths in some form of creativity, don't they?

29
00:03:05,009 --> 00:03:11,637
Paintings, architecture, poetry, music, film these days.

30
00:03:13,058 --> 00:03:18,484
So it's not that creativity is stifled more, it's opened up.

31
00:03:18,885 --> 00:03:33,099
an endless possibility of creativity on moral, social, economic, religious themes, which are there as a teaching tool.

32
00:03:34,961 --> 00:03:36,623
There's no end to it.

33
00:03:36,783 --> 00:03:48,876
If you look at something, if you look at art, you can see that one end of it is sort of, what do you use, searching for the word base, pornographic

34
00:03:49,649 --> 00:04:17,529
in the biggest sense of that meaning just abusing people's emotions you could even say some of these films that come out of Hollywood which feed into people's greed and violence is pornographic there's no way that could be sexual and then you get films which are much more social or just pure entertainment or whatever but then you get films which are

35
00:04:18,218 --> 00:04:19,738
you know, have a deeper meaning.

36
00:04:21,680 --> 00:04:30,168
So, it's not that spiritual insight undermines creativity.

37
00:04:30,309 --> 00:04:31,249
I would say the opposite.

38
00:04:31,810 --> 00:04:35,992
What it does is it stops certain types of creativity because it does harm.

39
00:04:36,814 --> 00:04:37,514
Simple as that, really.

40
00:04:40,197 --> 00:04:43,579
So, the process.

41
00:04:43,720 --> 00:04:48,124
When the Buddha was... You see, the Buddha said that...

42
00:04:49,858 --> 00:04:50,480
I'll put it this way.

43
00:04:50,540 --> 00:04:57,346
When he was asked what he taught, the way he would express things was always in this negative sense.

44
00:04:57,607 --> 00:05:00,790
We read it out, the unborn, the undying, etc.

45
00:05:01,130 --> 00:05:04,653
Not that there's no self, but he would talk about not-self.

46
00:05:05,975 --> 00:05:07,937
So he would be accused of annihilationism.

47
00:05:08,137 --> 00:05:09,759
That was the normal accusation.

48
00:05:11,081 --> 00:05:17,627
And he insists that the only thing that was annihilated, completely destroyed, was greed, hatred and delusion.

49
00:05:18,369 --> 00:05:18,769
Nothing else.

50
00:05:19,778 --> 00:05:27,749
So, everything we have is given back to us, renewed, you might say, refreshed, purified.

51
00:05:28,410 --> 00:05:32,574
So the mind is returned in its purity.

52
00:05:32,634 --> 00:05:35,338
The heart, see, it's the same with emotions.

53
00:05:36,240 --> 00:05:45,853
You might get the impression that vipassana, watching the emotions arise and pass away and fade away, that you're moving towards a sort of...

54
00:05:46,694 --> 00:05:57,149
I don't know, like a blob, you know, at the end you've got no emotions, and you're just sitting there like a non-emotional blob.

55
00:05:58,711 --> 00:06:03,499
But it's not true, because what happens is the emotions are transformed.

56
00:06:04,300 --> 00:06:07,805
The emotions are transformed, and that's the importance of this metta practice.

57
00:06:10,129 --> 00:06:12,432
So everything that...

58
00:06:12,630 --> 00:06:20,524
that everything is given back to us, renewed, refreshed, reformed, however you wish to look at it.

59
00:06:21,786 --> 00:06:22,908
And that's the process.

60
00:06:34,887 --> 00:06:35,970
Yeah?

61
00:06:35,990 --> 00:06:36,089
Yeah.

62
00:06:48,067 --> 00:06:53,714
On that similar line, you can make a distinction between reaction and response.

63
00:06:54,836 --> 00:07:02,545
So a reaction is coming from conditioning, from the past dictating the present, dictating the future.

64
00:07:03,708 --> 00:07:05,569
You know, if I did that, that wouldn't be me.

65
00:07:05,910 --> 00:07:07,172
That's a lovely one, isn't it?

66
00:07:07,192 --> 00:07:08,333
I've heard people say that.

67
00:07:08,694 --> 00:07:10,014
If I did that, it wouldn't be me.

68
00:07:10,755 --> 00:07:15,341
So they've got this really hard idea of who they are.

69
00:07:16,654 --> 00:07:27,685
And most of our actions, most of our thoughts are continuation of past habitual ways of thinking and feeling and reacting to things.

70
00:07:28,687 --> 00:07:36,995
So when that's purified, then we respond to a situation coming from a different level.

71
00:07:37,076 --> 00:07:38,637
Not conditioning, but from wisdom.

72
00:07:39,939 --> 00:07:41,000
Compassion and wisdom.

73
00:07:41,721 --> 00:07:46,105
So the response is creative because of that.

74
00:07:46,810 --> 00:07:48,531
Conditioning isn't creative.

75
00:07:48,632 --> 00:07:53,338
Conditioning just completely, constantly makes you go round the same circle.

76
00:07:53,879 --> 00:07:55,141
That's the meaning of karma.

77
00:07:59,026 --> 00:08:04,612
If you look at your life, you look back, you'll see that there are rounds of behaviour.

78
00:08:05,014 --> 00:08:07,857
You keep falling into the same sort of pit.

79
00:08:09,920 --> 00:08:16,108
If you haven't seen that yet, if you don't think that's happened, then you haven't looked closely enough.

80
00:08:16,492 --> 00:08:18,355
Because that's what karma means.

81
00:08:18,454 --> 00:08:25,603
It means that you're on this wheel of going round and round.

82
00:08:27,427 --> 00:08:32,212
If you want to use a psychodynamic term, that's the meaning of neurosis.

83
00:08:32,332 --> 00:08:34,916
You keep going round and round the same thing.

84
00:08:34,936 --> 00:08:36,937
An obsession.

85
00:08:36,957 --> 00:08:39,140
Obsessiveness.

86
00:08:39,160 --> 00:08:46,230
So when that's clarified, when that's cleared out, then there is a spontaneity

87
00:08:46,514 --> 00:09:14,427
in the present moment which has to be totally creative because now you're not coming from a fixed idea or a fixed habit it's coming more from wisdom and wisdom simply means that you really see the situation as it really is not as you would want it to be hope it to be how it ought to be just as it is and that clarity allows you to respond

88
00:09:15,015 --> 00:09:16,998
in a way which feels spontaneous.

89
00:09:19,961 --> 00:09:28,191
It's spontaneous because it's not coming from a habit, it's coming from a preconceived idea of how to behave.

90
00:09:30,514 --> 00:09:37,142
And that's one of the meanings of living in the moment, living in the present moment.

91
00:09:57,642 --> 00:10:02,347
Yeah?

92
00:10:02,368 --> 00:10:02,849
Something like that.

93
00:10:02,948 --> 00:10:13,162
How is it possible to put into practice Buddhist teaching and method into the wider society, and how does it relate?

94
00:10:14,543 --> 00:10:15,104
That's a very...

95
00:10:15,585 --> 00:10:19,048
I mean, there are books written on that.

96
00:10:19,068 --> 00:10:20,350
Engaged Buddhism, you know?

97
00:10:20,851 --> 00:10:21,673
Engaged Buddhism.

98
00:10:25,096 --> 00:10:27,480
Just in short, or actually we're saying brief,

99
00:10:28,894 --> 00:10:30,777
without going into too much detail.

100
00:10:31,937 --> 00:10:40,706
The Eightfold Path, you see, you'll notice that the Buddha begins with right understanding, so there's a correction in the way we see things.

101
00:10:41,346 --> 00:10:42,967
This affects our attitude.

102
00:10:44,068 --> 00:10:52,677
And then both this understanding and attitude express themselves in right speech, right action, right livelihood.

103
00:10:53,096 --> 00:10:58,142
Now, logically speaking, you didn't have to put right livelihood in there because it's part of right action.

104
00:11:01,278 --> 00:11:06,624
But livelihood is, in that wider sense, how we affect society.

105
00:11:08,405 --> 00:11:13,711
So from a personal point of view, what we do in society is our teaching.

106
00:11:18,837 --> 00:11:26,886
You see, every time you move, every time you say something, you're presenting an example, whether you like it or not.

107
00:11:26,907 --> 00:11:30,711
Other people might not see it as that, or accept it as that, but

108
00:11:30,943 --> 00:12:00,883
everybody in that sense is a teacher and as you know if you happen to tell somebody that you now meditate you know you're meditating in a Buddhist fashion and that is all the past now and then they see you wandering around the streets completely drunk and you know they say oh that's what meditation does for you so as soon as you state who you are to what you do there comes a sort of

109
00:12:01,352 --> 00:12:31,004
responsibility with it so when it comes to the wider society each of us have to consider how you know what we do what we support the way we vote what we say about things that are happening in the world and to make sure it's true to our own understanding and whether we like it or not that goes into that goes into

110
00:12:32,351 --> 00:12:36,859
the general understanding of a society of mankind, doesn't it?

111
00:12:36,938 --> 00:12:38,041
It feeds into it.

112
00:12:38,061 --> 00:12:40,684
It's like stuff coming into the computer.

113
00:12:41,385 --> 00:12:46,793
As soon as you say something, it becomes part of, what would you call it, human thought patterns.

114
00:12:46,813 --> 00:12:52,582
It's there in the ether, you might say.

115
00:12:52,602 --> 00:12:59,493
Specifically, this is what Buddhism is working with.

116
00:12:59,793 --> 00:13:01,296
It's one of the areas it's working with.

117
00:13:02,373 --> 00:13:08,839
How do you translate teachings that were given 2,500 years ago into a modern society?

118
00:13:09,600 --> 00:13:11,000
And there's lots.

119
00:13:12,402 --> 00:13:16,666
Personally, you could read of people like Ken, what's his name?

120
00:13:16,745 --> 00:13:19,548
Ken Jones, he's written a nice book on that.

121
00:13:20,750 --> 00:13:28,517
Everybody, there's a lot of people now who are trying to make sense of that, trying to make sense of, you know, what would a Buddhist economy mean?

122
00:13:28,557 --> 00:13:29,577
What would a...

123
00:13:29,827 --> 00:13:43,644
What would a Buddhist society look like without getting into idealism, some sort of, somebody called it, bootopia?

124
00:13:44,265 --> 00:13:55,919
That wouldn't be particularly Buddhist to have some sort of idealistic end point, because then you're imposing upon a future an idea which you've had in the past.

125
00:13:56,179 --> 00:13:57,422
That's exactly what you don't want to do.

126
00:13:59,225 --> 00:14:25,636
so when the Buddha is formulating the order you can see he's not got a particular ideal he's working with the forms that were already there in society for people who were living in this ascetic way so there's nothing particularly new about that there were plenty of people sleeping under trees and all that sort of stuff

127
00:14:27,220 --> 00:14:55,995
and it's understood that for the first 20 years such was the high caliber of people joining the orders that there was no need to make rules and then people of lesser caliber began to enter and did silly things and so you had to make a rule so these rules grew up and they grew up in a sort of peculiar way because there are rules there in the order which are to do with morality to do with

128
00:14:56,903 --> 00:15:26,352
things like thieving and sexual conduct and all that but a lot of them are also to do with the monastic relationship to lay people and to society even going down to the way we eat you're not supposed to suru suru and chapu chapu you're not supposed to slurp and chomp loudly these minute little rules and they're gone forever and

129
00:15:26,705 --> 00:15:29,708
An institution is defined by its rules, isn't it?

130
00:15:34,235 --> 00:15:36,058
That's what an institution is, its set of rules.

131
00:15:36,659 --> 00:15:42,649
Whether it's something like marriage, or something huge like the WTO.

132
00:15:44,871 --> 00:15:55,648
And in fact you could say that as soon as, even you yourself, even you yourself, if you live on your own, have your own rules and regulations, your own veneer,

133
00:15:56,471 --> 00:16:02,019
So when somebody comes in and says, I'll wash the pots, you get very irritated when they don't wash them the way you wash them.

134
00:16:02,038 --> 00:16:02,919
You're supposed to wash them, no.

135
00:16:04,381 --> 00:16:07,245
Polish on your shoes with the cloth, not the brush.

136
00:16:08,866 --> 00:16:12,892
I just remember that as a huge argument with my parents.

137
00:16:12,912 --> 00:16:16,635
When I was a kid, still hangs on in my mind, you know.

138
00:16:16,655 --> 00:16:17,717
I could only have been about eight.

139
00:16:21,923 --> 00:16:23,104
So...

140
00:16:24,738 --> 00:16:48,475
That whole area of how does the Buddhist teachings relate to society is something which is thought about a great deal these days and presumably will be a constant investigation of how the teachings relate to modern society.

141
00:16:48,495 --> 00:16:50,677
I can't see that really coming to an end as such.

142
00:17:03,854 --> 00:17:13,105
You all know of the N.E.B.D, the Network of Engaged Buddhists and the publication they make?

143
00:17:15,788 --> 00:17:16,989
Yeah?

144
00:17:17,009 --> 00:17:25,398
So that's, you know, they deal with all sorts of vegetarianism and all that sort of stuff.

145
00:17:25,419 --> 00:17:29,284
I used to be active in that in the early days, the peace, what was it called then?

146
00:17:31,266 --> 00:17:32,346
Peace, something peace.

147
00:17:32,366 --> 00:17:32,847
We used to

148
00:17:33,452 --> 00:18:00,355
on those peace marches and we were we had the sort of arrogance of bringing peace to the peace march we hit people who became unpeaceful now we would we would sit from a great height peace

149
00:18:03,810 --> 00:18:09,576
Yeah?

150
00:18:10,136 --> 00:18:12,299
How to best use one's time?

151
00:18:14,362 --> 00:18:16,523
As a monk, nun or householder?

152
00:18:16,544 --> 00:18:25,272
As a householder, how much time to spend on oneself meditating, meditation contemplation, and with others doing good service to others?

153
00:18:26,074 --> 00:18:30,357
What does the Buddha say?

154
00:18:34,439 --> 00:18:47,298
Well, I don't think it's a case of a person saying, just to answer the first part of the question, whether one should be a monastic or not.

155
00:18:47,459 --> 00:18:51,084
I don't think it arises like that.

156
00:18:51,505 --> 00:19:03,061
I remember the old, well I knew it was very old, Jnana Ponica, who wrote The Heart of Buddhist Meditation, which is still the classic,

157
00:19:05,404 --> 00:19:14,434
And it seems as though somebody came to see him, a few people came to see him, and they were talking about monastic life and what it was all about.

158
00:19:16,076 --> 00:19:23,945
And there was a woman there said to him, but supposing we all became monks and nuns?

159
00:19:23,965 --> 00:19:28,230
And he said, don't worry my dear, it won't happen.

160
00:19:31,834 --> 00:19:34,196
I think it's not a

161
00:19:34,615 --> 00:19:45,926
It's not a case of a choice of being a monastic or a householder.

162
00:19:46,387 --> 00:19:48,128
One is simply drawn one way or the other.

163
00:19:48,829 --> 00:19:53,375
Not to say that people don't try or, you know, spend a bit of part of their life.

164
00:19:53,414 --> 00:19:58,881
There's a lot of people, I feel, a lot of Westerners who've become monks and nuns for a while.

165
00:19:59,521 --> 00:20:02,605
In fact, most of those who pass on to teachers have spent time in the order.

166
00:20:03,145 --> 00:20:04,487
You know, like Christopher Titmuss and

167
00:20:05,782 --> 00:20:08,826
Even Joseph Goldstein I think spent a month or two.

168
00:20:14,893 --> 00:20:20,278
So it's not remember that the order is very fluid like that.

169
00:20:20,479 --> 00:20:22,300
In Burma you can join for any time.

170
00:20:23,662 --> 00:20:32,652
And I think that's a lovely thing because even if one is not drawn to it as a way of life for themselves it's a lovely thing to do

171
00:20:33,559 --> 00:20:37,767
And it connects you with the monastic orders.

172
00:20:37,826 --> 00:20:40,310
It gives you a sort of heart feeling for them.

173
00:20:40,451 --> 00:20:40,892
That's what I think.

174
00:20:45,259 --> 00:20:51,529
In terms of being a householder, how much time do you spend on yourself, meditation, contemplation, or with others, doing good and all that?

175
00:20:52,010 --> 00:20:53,834
Well, that's very individualistic, isn't it?

176
00:20:55,415 --> 00:20:57,660
The split is rather false, really.

177
00:21:00,694 --> 00:21:04,480
At first it does seem that meditation is here and everything else is over there.

178
00:21:05,121 --> 00:21:08,305
And I'm only really doing spiritual practice when I'm sitting in meditation.

179
00:21:10,367 --> 00:21:13,951
And that's a false split, of course, because it's right there in the Eightfold Path.

180
00:21:14,012 --> 00:21:17,076
That right livelihood is part of the path.

181
00:21:18,117 --> 00:21:28,811
So somehow you have to make your work and what you do in society, you have to make it material to your spiritual life.

182
00:21:31,626 --> 00:21:33,088
That's your responsibility to yourself.

183
00:21:35,711 --> 00:21:40,655
And I can talk a bit more about that tomorrow.

184
00:21:41,317 --> 00:21:44,359
But that's very important.

185
00:21:44,740 --> 00:21:52,348
When we're in meditation, those of you who've done a course, we also create that sort of hierarchy even within a meditation retreat.

186
00:21:52,409 --> 00:21:53,390
Sitting is important.

187
00:21:53,670 --> 00:21:55,751
Walking is a little less important.

188
00:21:55,771 --> 00:21:58,275
And everything else we're doing during the day, like eating, is unimportant.

189
00:21:59,503 --> 00:22:03,990
So the mind gets concentrated in meditation and then loses it all for the rest of the day.

190
00:22:04,730 --> 00:22:12,519
But when you realize that every moment of the day is concerned with establishing this mindfulness, then of course it doesn't matter what you're doing.

191
00:22:13,701 --> 00:22:19,308
It doesn't matter what you're doing, as long as you're being mindful.

192
00:22:19,328 --> 00:22:28,059
Even now you see, as you're listening to me, you can be attentive and still generally feel what's going on in your body.

193
00:22:28,596 --> 00:22:32,501
it can be quite a spacious, restful awareness.

194
00:22:33,462 --> 00:22:46,800
And when a speaker is saying something which is asking for more attention, then one loses attention on the body, one loses that contact with the body, one becomes attentive only to the spoken word.

195
00:22:47,781 --> 00:22:55,853
Now, to be focused in on something like that, or to have the wide focus, it's all meditation, it's all awareness.

196
00:22:56,238 --> 00:23:09,037
So what we have to stress to ourselves is that the object of awareness is not awareness.

197
00:23:09,057 --> 00:23:14,224
The object of awareness, in other words what you're aware of, is not the awareness.

198
00:23:15,467 --> 00:23:24,861
So whether you're aware of, in your meditation, a single arising of a sensation, or you're aware of the whole body sensation, the whole body feeling,

199
00:23:26,461 --> 00:23:29,203
It's all awareness.

200
00:23:29,223 --> 00:23:38,615
And you can be aware of transience, the rising and falling away of a single sensation and you can also be aware of it in the wider sense of the coming and going of seasons.

201
00:23:41,097 --> 00:23:42,618
The arising and falling of a human being.

202
00:23:42,699 --> 00:23:53,852
Every time somebody dies whom you know that's also reminding us of the transience of life, the impermanence of it.

203
00:23:56,228 --> 00:24:06,179
So to develop the meditative mind, to develop the contemplative meditative mind, to develop this wisdom, that's a constant effort.

204
00:24:06,219 --> 00:24:08,221
You can't take a holiday.

205
00:24:08,981 --> 00:24:11,403
You can't take a break now and do something else.

206
00:24:12,365 --> 00:24:14,748
Every time you do that you create another bad habit.

207
00:24:14,928 --> 00:24:16,148
You go back on old habits.

208
00:24:17,810 --> 00:24:24,278
And that's why it takes so long because we make this big effort, we make an effort in meditation

209
00:24:24,730 --> 00:24:26,192
And then we go home and forget all about it.

210
00:24:32,538 --> 00:24:40,647
When I was living in Birmingham, I used to go and do a retreat every month at the local Vihara for a weekend.

211
00:24:41,749 --> 00:24:45,653
And I would always notice that the effect of that weekend would last till about Tuesday.

212
00:24:48,195 --> 00:24:52,340
It sort of began to fade completely out by Wednesday and Thursday.

213
00:24:53,906 --> 00:25:00,236
So that's it you see, but over a period of time it sort of had an effect.

214
00:25:01,577 --> 00:25:09,009
So you have to have that sort of patience, perseverance.

215
00:25:09,028 --> 00:25:13,816
So if you find yourself judging your spiritual progress, be careful.

216
00:25:14,176 --> 00:25:17,821
If you judge it over a week, you get very depressed.

217
00:25:18,712 --> 00:25:22,135
You have to make an effort and judge it over, say, 25 years.

218
00:25:23,498 --> 00:25:25,640
You think, I have moved, I can see I've moved.

219
00:25:29,462 --> 00:25:40,294
Because one thing we come across, isn't it, in our practice is how tenuous, how clinging these habits are.

220
00:25:40,794 --> 00:25:41,394
They go deep.

221
00:25:45,959 --> 00:25:47,961
So when it comes to daily life,

222
00:25:48,733 --> 00:26:00,904
how much time you spend on yourself and how much time you spend with others is very much to do with your circumstance and your inclination, your personal inclination.

223
00:26:00,964 --> 00:26:08,131
Some people are more drawn to contemplative life, others more to an active life.

224
00:26:08,151 --> 00:26:10,753
It's just up to you to decide, to get that balance.

225
00:26:11,795 --> 00:26:15,538
It's the balance you want, so that you feel your life is balanced.

226
00:26:15,557 --> 00:26:17,880
You've got enough time for yourself and enough time for others.

227
00:26:19,413 --> 00:26:20,394
And of course it changes.

228
00:26:20,433 --> 00:26:24,057
It changes at different times in your lives and depending on what's happening around you.

229
00:26:24,959 --> 00:26:25,920
So it's nothing fixed.

230
00:26:26,181 --> 00:26:32,587
You don't get the idea of some sort of mathematical equation.

231
00:26:47,124 --> 00:26:47,344
Yeah?

