298
00:35:11,268 --> 00:35:13,371
How can I cultivate the negative?

299
00:35:15,253 --> 00:35:19,097
I think you mean undermine, is it?

300
00:35:21,601 --> 00:35:24,224
Anybody wrote that?

301
00:35:24,425 --> 00:35:24,764
It is...

302
00:35:25,538 --> 00:35:32,885
It is a weakness in me that I am ashamed of, but have difficulty in letting go.

303
00:35:33,246 --> 00:35:37,592
It is an intolerance of myself and an intolerance of others and things.

304
00:35:38,632 --> 00:35:42,657
I think everybody suffers from that to some extent, intolerance.

305
00:35:46,963 --> 00:35:54,972
Well, intolerance is it comes down to that

306
00:35:55,255 --> 00:35:57,577
not wanting things to be the way they are.

307
00:35:59,278 --> 00:36:01,041
You become frustrated by it.

308
00:36:01,721 --> 00:36:08,367
And if it's very frustrating, if you take a position, this is not the way it should be, then you become intolerant.

309
00:36:08,648 --> 00:36:15,253
Then all you want to do is get rid of that which annoys you, which you think shouldn't be there.

310
00:36:16,054 --> 00:36:20,639
So, this goes back to this whole idea of patience.

311
00:36:21,260 --> 00:36:24,282
And patience, I think, is based on

312
00:36:24,635 --> 00:36:54,152
acceptance you know this is the way things are that's a lovely little sort of mantra this is this is the way things are now this is the way it is yeah when you walk into a situation or something happens you know just keep saying that now this is the way it is you see until you've actually until you've actually come down to that position of this is the way not this is the way it ought not to be or I want it to be or I expected it to be or it should be you know what I mean all those

313
00:36:54,706 --> 00:37:07,860
You see, when you get down to it and you say, this is the way it is, then I think you'll find patience arising easily within that.

314
00:37:07,880 --> 00:37:08,039
Yeah?

315
00:37:09,400 --> 00:37:20,293
And that intolerance, the intolerance towards ourselves, I mean, that also is an acceptance of, well, this is the way it is.

316
00:37:20,612 --> 00:37:23,615
This is the way I am at this present, or this, be careful here,

317
00:37:23,831 --> 00:37:26,416
This is the conditioning as it is now.

318
00:37:26,938 --> 00:37:34,996
So if I find myself, say, anxious again over something stupid, over something silly, then I say, OK, this is the way it is now.

319
00:37:36,559 --> 00:37:37,581
This is the way it is now.

320
00:37:38,523 --> 00:37:43,713
And then you work with that, letting the anxiety pass, etc., etc.

321
00:37:56,670 --> 00:38:13,387
And once you've worked with that a little while, once you've allowed the intolerance to die away, that sense of, you know, it shouldn't be like this, like that person, this is the way it is, then that's when you find metta having a very strong effect.

322
00:38:14,146 --> 00:38:23,556
Once that's died, as soon as you wish goodwill towards somebody or to yourself, then that creates a different attitude, you see.

323
00:38:24,007 --> 00:38:35,081
And that attitude of openness, kindness, gentleness, acceptance begins to undermine all this business of, it should be like this, etc., etc.

324
00:38:36,244 --> 00:38:47,458
And although I'm coming very late to it in my practice, I'm really beginning to see that the practice of metta is, I think it's quite crucial really.

325
00:38:49,581 --> 00:38:50,742
It's quite crucial.

326
00:38:51,952 --> 00:38:54,054
Because it's to do with developing right attitude.

327
00:38:56,257 --> 00:39:04,226
When you're meditating, for instance, and you feel, for instance, you feel very impatient with yourself because the mind's wandering so much.

328
00:39:05,887 --> 00:39:07,289
And you're judging yourself, you see.

329
00:39:07,349 --> 00:39:11,472
So that immediately becomes your object to observe, to feel, to experience.

330
00:39:11,793 --> 00:39:12,653
Judging, judging.

331
00:39:12,853 --> 00:39:14,755
And you feel the self-hatred.

332
00:39:15,617 --> 00:39:17,059
So, all that sort of stuff.

333
00:39:17,739 --> 00:39:20,442
When that dies away, you see, then

334
00:39:21,434 --> 00:39:31,869
there has to be that effort to turn upon oneself with compassion, to turn the stream of compassion within oneself by offering oneself good wishes.

335
00:39:33,271 --> 00:39:36,976
And that eventually completely undermines the basis.

336
00:39:37,797 --> 00:39:41,603
You can't be loving and angry at the same time.

337
00:39:41,943 --> 00:39:43,224
That's the point.

338
00:39:43,244 --> 00:39:45,568
These two mental states can't exist together.

339
00:39:46,670 --> 00:39:51,356
So the more that we bend the mind towards being gentle, being kind

340
00:39:54,019 --> 00:40:23,942
that undermines those old habits with things like intolerance remember there's always a view and an opinion there are these three states conceit, view and attachment so if you take religious intolerance

341
00:40:24,208 --> 00:40:27,293
There's a view, very simple.

342
00:40:27,614 --> 00:40:28,454
I'm right, you're wrong.

343
00:40:29,757 --> 00:40:31,639
We can't get more simple than that.

344
00:40:32,019 --> 00:40:32,882
I'm right, you're wrong.

345
00:40:33,902 --> 00:40:35,905
There's a conceit there.

346
00:40:36,766 --> 00:40:38,168
I'm right, you're wrong.

347
00:40:39,811 --> 00:40:41,213
I've got it all right.

348
00:40:41,914 --> 00:40:43,516
And there's an attachment to it.

349
00:40:43,536 --> 00:40:45,559
There's a heart attachment to it.

350
00:40:48,384 --> 00:40:53,271
So the head is here with this is the truth, everything else is not the truth.

351
00:40:53,976 --> 00:41:00,344
there's an identity with it, I'm right, you're wrong, and there's a heart attachment to it.

352
00:41:01,387 --> 00:41:06,733
